## What Actually Clicked for Me

The thing that clicked most today is how the shared responsibility model from Day 16 and the concept of common controls are really the same idea expressed in different frameworks.

When AWS says "we are responsible for security of the cloud," they are describing a set of common controls that MyClinic inherits automatically by using AWS services. The physical security of data centers, the security of the hypervisor, the network infrastructure protections — these are all common controls in NIST RMF terms. They are implemented by AWS, documented in AWS compliance certifications, and inherited by every customer system running on AWS infrastructure.

Making that connection between the shared responsibility model and the RMF common control concept helped me see both frameworks more clearly. The shared responsibility model is the business and contractual framing. The NIST RMF common control concept is the security and compliance framing. They describe the same underlying reality.

The other thing that clicked is the documentation requirement. Inheriting a common control is not the same as ignoring it. The inheriting system still needs to document the inheritance — identifying which common control provider is responsible, what evidence demonstrates the control is in place, and any limitations or gaps that the inherited control does not fully address. That documentation is what makes the inheritance auditable and defensible.

