## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While researching today's topic I came across the **2021 Microsoft Exchange Server vulnerabilities** — a series of critical zero-day vulnerabilities that affected on-premises Exchange Server installations worldwide. Attackers exploited the vulnerabilities to gain access to email systems across thousands of organizations including healthcare providers.

What makes this case relevant to common controls is the contrast between organizations running Exchange on-premises and those using Microsoft's cloud-based Exchange Online service. For cloud customers, Microsoft had already patched the underlying infrastructure before the vulnerabilities were publicly disclosed — the fix was a common control delivered by the provider. On-premises customers had to apply patches themselves, and many were compromised during the window between public disclosure and patch application.

This is one of the concrete security benefits of the common control model in cloud environments. When a vulnerability affects infrastructure that a cloud provider manages as a common control, the provider can patch it across their entire infrastructure simultaneously. The inheriting customer benefits from that patch without having to do anything — and without the window of exposure that on-premises customers face.

For OpenMRS on AWS, this means that vulnerabilities in the underlying EC2 hypervisor, the RDS database engine managed layer, or the S3 infrastructure are patched by AWS as common control maintenance. MyClinic does not manage those patches and does not face the patch lag risk for those components. That is a real and meaningful security benefit of the cloud hosting model — one that the common control framework helps make explicit and documented.

